This was gonna sustain my upvote until the offset page, where it singlehandedly reversed my vote entirely. I think that going through all the legwork of introducing a potentially amazing idea like , but in the most spectacularly ludicrous way possible.

If you're gonna introduce multiple disparate, suspension-stretching ideas, you can't simply throw one right after another and not give it the proper breathing room it needs. You can't tell me that 4000 is an entire uninhabitated state (itself an already wild idea, but one you try to make utterly convincing even with the holes that sprout up from it), then say 4000 is the veil and call it a day. Even moreso, attempting to follow that statement up and justify it would make the article utterly too long and clunky while still being just as impossible to accept. Since you're going for this tactic, why not just leave it at the first article? You'd simply need to make minor adjustments throughout to strengthen your implication instead of spilling it out on a new page, and not tip your hand so much on the original page as to make it difficult to buy in. No two ways about it; this is supremely difficult to buy into, and I feel like better can be done nowadays from any author than simply stating a complex or unique idea and going .







